<HL>
   Europe's New-Car Sales Increase
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- New car sales in Europe in March rose 0.9% from
a year earlier, possibly signaling a slowdown after a healthy
start to the year.
   The market is "definitely not maintaining the momentum"
displayed in February and January, when car sales were up
2.1% and 4% on the year, respectively, said Stephen Reitman,
an industry analyst at UBS-Phillips &amp; Drew Ltd.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Statistics from 12 nations that usually account for 94% of
Western Europe's passenger car sales showed new car
registrations totaled 1,270,000 in March, up 22% from
1,040,000 in February and up from 1,260,000 a year earlier.
   In March, sales were off on the year in five of the
countries included in the survey: Portugal, Spain, Sweden,
Switzerland and the U.K. Among the gainers, West Germany
posted a 2% rise, while France rose 6.8% and Italy rose 3.4%.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0155
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0155.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   B.F. Goodrich Co. Expansion
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   GR
</CO>
<LP>
   AKRON, Ohio -- B.F. Goodrich Co. said it will invest about
$14 million to expand capacity to produce hydrophilic resins
at Calvert City, Ky., and Pohang, South Korea.
   The expansion, which is scheduled to be completed in
mid-1991, will increase the company's world-wide capacity for
the materials by 35%, Goodrich said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Hydrophilic resins are additives used as thickening and
suspension agents in cosmetics and personal-care products,
and a number of other uses, the company said.
   Goodrich is a plastics, specialty chemicals and aerospace
products concern.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0154
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0154.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Allied Irish Banks
   Offers to Acquire
   Maryland Bank
   ----
   By Craig Forman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B7
</SO>
<CO>
   AIB+ BBB X.FMD
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   LONDON -- Allied Irish Banks PLC offered to buy Baltimore
Bancorp. for $217 million, expanding the big Irish bank's
U.S. presence and continuing the spate of U.S. bids by
overseas companies.
   The bid, made in a letter Friday to Baltimore Bancorp.'s
board from AIB's First Maryland Bancorp unit, is "unsolicited
but friendly," said Diarmuid Moore, director of strategy for
Dublin-based AIB. In a phone interview, he didn't rule out a
hostile bid if AIB's overture is rejected. But, he added, "we
are very anxious to conclude a friendly deal, and think the
offer represents full and fair value."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Though Baltimore said its board will consider the
$17-a-share bid "in due course," the bank indicated yesterday
it considers the offer unwelcome. In a letter to First
Maryland, Baltimore Chairman Harry L. Robinson took "direct
issue with {First Maryland's} statement that the offer is
delivered `in a spirit of cordiality and goodwill.' " Mr.
Robinson said AIB didn't call to say the bid was coming, and
requested a response by tomorrow. Such moves "could have only
been designed to create a hostile atmosphere and to place
pressure upon us. Please rest assured that we will not be
cowed by these tactics."
   AIB's First Maryland unit already has amassed a 4.9%
Baltimore stake for about $6.7 million. The offer values the
entire company's roughly 12.8 million common shares
outstanding at about $217 million.
   At roughly a 47% premium to Baltimore Bancorp.'s Friday
close of $11.75 a share on the New York Stock Exchange, the
offer seems aimed at elbowing out other potential suitors. It
values Baltimore Bancorp. at 12.7 times 1989 earnings and
about 1.1 times tangible net worth, according to AIB.
   People involved in the bid expect Baltimore to seek a
white-knight counterbidder, if the board chooses to fight.
Baltimore "would probably consider a white knight," said
AIB's Mr. Moore. "But we would be surprised if there is a
better offer. We didn't start on basis of pitching it {the
bid} low and trying to get it for free." Analysts added that
recent jitters in the U.S. financial industry because of
souring real-estate lending may keep interest low.
   In March, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. lowered ratings on about
$72 million of Baltimore subordinated debt to double-B-plus
from triple-B, citing the firm's "substantial concentration"
in commercial real estate lending and volatile funding
sources.
   In composite trading yesterday on the New York Stock
Exchange, Baltimore shares closed at $15, up $3.25.
   Shares in AIB, which also announced a 1-for-6
share-purchase right to raise 162 million Irish pounds
($259.5 million) to help finance the purchase and for general
purposes, fell 14 pence to 235 pence on London's Stock
Exchange.
   Baltimore would be a significant addition to AIB's network
in the mid-Atlantic states, and would continue an expansion
by big overseas banks in U.S. retail banking. Such banks as
National Westminster Bank PLC, Royal Bank of Scotland and
many Japanese banks already are amassing significant retail
presences on America's East and West Coasts as squeezed
margins at home are making the U.S. market seem more
alluring.
   U.S. targets also seem reasonably priced, and the weakened
U.S. market for junk securities has hamstrung some domestic
U.S. bidders. Against that backdrop, overseas bidders have
been snapping up U.S. assets lately. More than $2 billion in
deals have been announced in the past week alone, including
the purchases of retailer Saks Fifth Avenue and industrial
group Norton Co.
   AIB already is Maryland's second-biggest bank after
acquiring control of Baltimore's First Maryland Bancorp in
1988 for a total of $520 million. Buying fifth-largest
Baltimore Bancorp., also based in Baltimore, would boost its
asset base in the area by $3.4 billion to about $11 billion.
But it would still remain well behind leader MNC Financial
Inc., with about $23 billion in assets.
   Analysts favor AIB to win the battle. Chris Wheeler, a
banking analyst at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in London
said, "I think they are going to win. AIB obviously is
offering a hell of a premium in what is a worrying banking
market." But, he added, "I think the reason they announced
now was they were worried someone else may be out there." en
   Rodgin Cohen at Sullivan and Cromwell in New York, who is
representing Baltimore Bancorp., said this is the first time
a foreign bank has launched a hostile transaction.
   "Because of the way it came, it has to be treated as a
hostile offer," Mr. Cohen said, noting that First Maryland
delivered a letter to his client late Friday afternoon and
then released it to the media soon afterwards. "You just
don't do things like that and call it a friendly deal."
   He added that he has always advised foreign banks to avoid
hostile deals because the Federal Reserve increases its
scrutiny and forces them to play by the same rules as U.S.
banks, which can be more restrictive than foreign rules.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0153
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0153.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Labor Letter:
   A Special News Report on People
   And Their Jobs in Offices,
   Fields and Factories
   ----
   By Selwyn Feinstein
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   LABOR UIS
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, MEDICINE, DENTISTRY (HEA)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   JOB HOPPING: Executives think it's risky. But a challenge
can be tempting.
   Managers who might have sought greener pastures in the
past "are sitting tight" now, says Harris Corp. "There's a
degree of caution that wasn't there a year ago."
Kimberly-Clark Corp. still sees lots of applications, but
most come from executives pushed out or in imminent danger.
"The ones with the good companies are staying," it observes.
Charles Maschal, president of the National Association of
Executive Recruiters, explains switching now can be "very
risky" because the last one hired could well be the first one
fired.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But Adolph Coors Co. says one recent ad drew "an
extraordinarily large number of responses," many from
executives who are secure. "Most people, regardless of
whether they're truly happy in their jobs, are keeping their
eyes open," it says. Chrysler Corp. says it believes few
executives today are willing to trade away safe jobs for the
promises of a new position. But it, too, says the lure
sometimes can be irresistible.
   "A lot of top executives love a challenge," even more than
job security, the auto maker says.
                                                                                                       

   WHO'S TRANSFERRED? If you fit this profile, get ready to
pack.
   Salesmen 31 to 40 years old earning $30,000 to $50,000 a
year are most likely to be relocated by their companies, a
survey by Atlas Van Lines finds. And they are apt to be moved
every three to five years. Female workers can feel secure, or
more likely feel victims of an old bias. Nearly one in three
companies says it didn't transfer any female workers last
year. At another third, less than 5% of the transferees were
women.
   If you were transferred last year, you probably left New
York or Denver and headed for Washington, D.C., or
California, a separate survey by PHH Corp.'s relocation unit
shows. The company helped clients move 903 workers into the
Big Apple but assisted 1,592 in moving out, for a net outflow
of 689. Denver lost 503. The nation's capital, by contrast,
gained 459 workers while San Francisco and Los Angeles each
added more than 200 through PHH. Much of the activity
reflected cost-cutting consolidations.
                                                                                                       

   INNER-CITY KIDS find summer jobs at firms eager to provide
for tomorrow.
   "Urban students, mainly minorities, aren't always aware of
the opportunities that exist in corporations," says
Prudential Insurance Co. So it hires 28 youngsters for
entry-level jobs and helps fund training programs for others.
At York Ladder Inc., seven high-school students can look
forward to a summer of lifting and loading in 90 degree heat,
where the company hopes they'll learn "humility and humanity
that can translate into the future when they become leaders
in a corporation."
   Wickes Corp. will hire 150 neighborhood youths to work at
15 Builders Emporium Home Centers. "We feel we have a
responsibility to help prepare them for their future," it
explains. Vons Cos. teams with Pepsi-Cola and a local
foundation to award bagging jobs and motivational lectures to
more than 50 inner-city teen-agers who do well in school.
"Sometimes they tend not to be recognized as much as kids
with athletic achievements," it says.
   In Chicago, 250 firms in Hire the Future will take on
3,300 C grade-or-better students; dropouts are shunned.
                                                                                                       

   JOB HUNTERS, BEWARE] Postal inspectors say a confidence
artist is using help-wanted ads in a credit-card scam. He's
requesting resumes for a high-paying job and then calling for
Social Security and driver's license numbers that are used to
tap the applicant's credit line.
                                                                                                       

   ESOPs GREW SHARPLY in 1989, with large public companies
worried about takeovers dominating the expansion, says the
National Center for Employee Ownership.
                                                                                                       

   UNISYS CORP. signs up instructors from Temple University
to teach workers being laid off at a Philadelphia plant how
to start and operate their own businesses.
                                                                                                       

   VOLUNTEERISM LIVES, but it's getting weaker. One in five
Americans donates time to religious, civic, educational or
other groups, the Bureau of Labor Statistics says. That's
down from one in four in 1974.
                                                                                                       

   BEST LAID PLANS: Strategies fail because managers don't
understand.
   That's the view of top executives who formulate the
objectives that somehow get lost down the corporate ladder. A
survey by consultant Booz, Allen &amp; Hamilton finds that only
37% of the senior officials think other key managers
completely understand new business goals. Only 4% of the top
bosses think middle managers totally understand.
   Not surprisingly, compliance drops with understanding, to
the point where nearly half the top executives believe that
middle managers go along with new strategies at best
partially or not at all. The top bosses believe pay policies
at their companies may be working against the strategy
changes they try to push.
   Half say performance rewards "actually encourage
counterproductive or narrowly focused behavior."
                                                                                                       

   THE CHECKOFF: Three of four male pediatricians -- but less
than half their female colleagues -- believe children a year
or younger are harmed when their mothers work full time, says
the American Academy of Pediatrics and Working Mother
magazine. . . . A federal court rules an agency violates the
age discrimination act when it doesn't hire a 64-year-old
dentist for an entry-level post because he knows too much,
consultant Alexander &amp; Alexander advises.
</TEXT>
