<HL>
   How Quarterly Study
   Evaluates Brokers'
   Allocation of Assets
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C27
</SO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The quarterly Wall Street Journal-Wilshire
Associates study of asset allocation includes the 10
brokerage houses with the largest number of registered
representatives.
   Some companies publish more than one set of
asset-allocation recommendations. Within reason, they may
pick which set they want to be judged by, provided they
specify in advance. Two companies, PaineWebber Inc. and
Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co., recently changed the asset-allocation
blend tracked in the study.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   PaineWebber formerly used a theoretical asset-allocation
model developed by Edward Kerschner and Charles Pradilla. Its
neutral reading calls for a 33.3% position in each of three
assets, stocks, bonds, and cash. As of Jan. 31, PaineWebber
asked to be judged, instead, on its advice for a typical
balanced portfolio, in which stocks normally have heavier
weight.
   Goldman Sachs, previously judged on its advice to large
pension funds, has asked to be judged as of March 31 on its
advice for a smaller, aggressive pension fund. Strategist
Steven Einhorn said he believes this advice more closely
approximates what individual investors should follow.
   Other companies with more than one asset-allocation blend
are tracked as follows:
   Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. is judged on its
recommendations for a "small, aggressive fund"; A.G. Edwards
&amp; Sons Inc. on a "growth and income" portfolio; Kidder,
Peabody &amp; Co. on an "individual balanced" portfolio, and
Raymond, James &amp; Associates Inc. on advice to "young urban
professionals."
   The study disregards the cost of trading, mainly to make
the results comparable to market averages. In practice, of
course, people who often adjust their investment blends may
incur high commissions.
   Each house's advice is mirrored in a theoretical
portfolio. Holdings are adjusted whenever the advice changes,
and also on the last day of each month, to keep assets in the
recommended ratio.
   Investments are assumed to do as well as the following
indexes: the Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index for stocks;
the Merrill Lynch corporate and government master bond index
for bonds; 90-day Treasury bills for cash; the National
Council of Real Estate Investment Fiduciaries/Frank Russell
Co. index for real estate; and the average monthly price of
gold for tangible assets.
   (See related story: "Your Money Matters: "Ten Brokers Give
Asset-Allocating Advice" -- WSJ May 1, 1990).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0147
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0147.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Japan's Global Factory-Research Project
   Is Seen by Some in West as Trojan Horse
   ----
   By Jacob M. Schlesinger
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A15
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN UTX ROK
</CO>
<IN>
INDUSTRIAL EQUIPMENT, MACHINE TOOLS (IND)
</IN>
<GV>
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
</GV>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- When Japan earlier this year launched a $1
billion project to revolutionize the world's factories, it
expected praise from grateful Americans and Europeans.
   Instead, it got egg on its face.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Intelligent Manufacturing System proposed by Japan is
a 10-year project to integrate existing factory technologies
from the major industrialized countries, to develop a
world-wide standard for future factory technologies, and to
pool international resources to create "21st century"
high-tech systems. The project, in the form of a consortium,
would include governments, companies and universities.
   Cut from the famous Japanese industrial-policy mold, the
proposed consortium has intrigued U.S. companies that can't
get similar backing for such programs at home. But it has
triggered an uproar in the U.S. and Europe, where some
officials say it smacks of a Japanese Trojan horse to take
over the world economy.
   Early last week, the Commerce Department hosted a
contentious meeting near Washington on the project with about
50 U.S. industry representatives. On Thursday, an assistant
secretary of commerce blasted the program at a congressional
hearing. Commerce officials plan to raise their concerns at
an annual meeting on bilateral science and technology
exchange this week.
   "We are very disturbed by the way the Japanese approached
this," says a senior Commerce official. "They don't want a
level playing field. They want to target our industries."
European Community officials echo those sentiments.
   The Japanese, who for years have been berated for keeping
research closed to outsiders, profess bemusement. "When we do
nothing, we are criticized. When we do something, we are
criticized," sighs Takeshi Isayama, director of the
industrial machinery division of the Ministry of
International Trade and Industry, or MITI, which is helping
fund the project.
   As the governments feud, United Technologies Corp. and
Rockwell International Corp. are signing up for the project,
and others have indicated interest. With the Bush
administration dead set against anything that smacks of an
industrial policy, some companies say, Americans looking for
such assistance might as well get it from the Japanese.
   "If our government isn't doing equally visionary things,
what would they have us do?" asks Stanley P. Krueger,
president of United Technologies' Japan office. "We can't sit
still in the U.S., turn off the lights and send our employees
home."
   Leo Reddy, president of the National Coalition for
Advanced Manufacturing in Washington, says he has serious
concerns about the program, but adds: "They're putting up the
money, our government isn't. It's a metaphor for our time, a
Sputnik. It dramatically underlines the fact the Japanese are
taking manufacturing very seriously."
   All these issues are likely to come up with growing
frequency, as the manufacturing consortium is just one of
many the Japanese government is opening up to foreign
companies. Last year, General Electric Co. and United
Technologies' Pratt &amp; Whitney subsidiary signed up for a MITI
project to develop a high-speed jet engine. That raised
hackles about the possibility that the U.S. companies would
leak technology in a field where the U.S. still has the
advantage. But, remarkably enough, it also brought together
two longtime bitter rivals to work on a project.
   The consortium was the brainchild of Hiroyuki Yoshikawa,
dean of Tokyo University's Faculty of Engineering and an
expert on manufacturing. The effort he began coordinating
last year now has 80 major Japanese companies on board.
   Dr. Yoshikawa's philosophy, outlined in the program
brochure, is that international cooperation in manufacturing
becomes essential as the shortage of skilled labor world-wide
requires more factory automation and technology costs rise.
Among other things, standardization simplifies applying
know-how around the world.
   Japan has long conducted industrial research this way.
Government-corporate-university consortia helped Japan catch
up in semiconductors and take the lead in high-definition
television. Such projects have been seen as vehicles for
national development, and closed to outsiders.
   But foreigners' lack of access to Japanese research is a
source of international tension. In the West, the most
important scientific work takes place in open university
laboratories, something the Japanese have diligently taken
advantage of. But in Japan, most work is done in closed
corporate facilities, and in closed consortia.
   A 1988 U.S.-Japan science and technology agreement was
meant to address such issues. Last year, Japan started the
Human Frontier Science Project, based in Strasbourg, France,
to fund international research. And Japan has been opening up
more of its own projects. Its superconductivity lab has nine
foreign corporate members. Last year, MITI opened all its
major consortia to foreign companies. In addition to the
engine project, it invited outsiders to help research
underground construction.
   MITI and Japanese companies will put up $600 million for
the manufacturing consortium in the next decade, with $200
million each from the U.S. and Europe. An international
research center will be set up in Europe or North America.
   Japanese researchers and government officials briefed
representatives of foreign companies and embassies in Tokyo
in January. The response was enthusiastic. But when word
filtered back to the U.S. and Europe, the reaction was
cooler.
   U.S. Commerce officials say the way the Japanese have
pursued the project hints of trying to sneak around official
channels. While the Japanese made some low-level U.S.
government contacts, they mainly have approached U.S.
industry directly, signing up the Society of Manufacturing
Engineers as the U.S. coordinator. When Commerce officials
complained to the Japanese Embassy in Washington last month,
they were told it was a Japanese private industry project.
   The European Community has had tighter control over direct
Japanese contact with companies. But it too has expressed
similar concerns. A few weeks ago, EC officials met with
Commerce officials to compare notes and responses.
   To some Westerners, the Japanese have a reason for
avoiding government contacts: the project, they say, is
structured to allow Japanese companies to suck up advanced
Western know-how. While Japan may already use more robots,
they say, the West is ahead in systems integration and
computer software.
   "It is directed at one of the few remaining areas where
the U.S. retains technological superiority," James L. Koontz,
president of Kingsbury Corp. and chairman of the National
Center for Manufacturing Sciences, testified before a Senate
commitee last month. "We would lose." Others argue that even
if everybody shares the technology, Japan will be the main
beneficiary because its companies are much quicker about
putting new techniques to use.
   To the Japanese, the project is a noble gesture. After
all, they say, study after study proclaims the U.S. is losing
its manufacturing prowess, while Japan pulls further ahead.
In fact, Japanese officials say they had to fight to convince
Japanese companies to participate. Says MITI's Mr. Isayama,
"A lot complained: Why do we have to expose our technology to
outsiders?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0146
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0146.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Your Money Matters:
   Ten Brokers Give Asset-Allocating Advice
   ----
   By John R. Dorfman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<CO>
   GE AGE S PA AXP SLH MER RJF
</CO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
PRECIOUS METALS, STONES, GOLD, SILVER (PCS)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   In "The Wizard of Oz" Dorothy reaches a fork in the road
and asks Scarecrow which way she should go. Scarecrow points
first left, then right, and finally says, "Of course, some
people do go both ways."
   It's a lot like that on Wall Street these days: Investors
can get plenty of advice on how to allocate their money among
stocks, bonds and cash -- but the advice points every which
way.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Of 10 major brokerage houses whose advice is regularly
tracked by this newspaper, only two currently recommend a
traditional allocation with 50% to 60% in stocks. Two suggest
a bigger helping of stocks; six others say to go light on
stocks for now.
   Amid rising interest rates, both stocks and bonds declined
in the first quarter. The best posture, hindsight shows, was
to be heavily in cash, as was advocated by PaineWebber Inc.
Cash means safe, short-term investments, such as Treasury
bills or money-market funds.
   Investors following the asset-allocation advice of nine of
the 10 brokerage houses would have lost a little money last
quarter, according to a study by this newspaper and Wilshire
Associates of Santa Monica, Calif. Investors following
PaineWebber's advice would have eked out a slim gain of 0.8%,
the study estimates.
   The brokers' advice has been better over the longer term.
Still, only three of the 10 companies' recommended investment
mixes beat a traditional, unchanging blend of 55% stocks, 35%
bonds, and 10% cash over the 12 months ended March 31. Over
the full term of the study, 39 months, five out of nine
companies beat that benchmark. Raymond James &amp; Associates
hasn't been giving asset-allocation advice for that long.
   Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., a unit of Prudential
Insurance Co. of America, led the rankings for the latest 12
months, with an estimated return of 18.4%. Prudential-Bache
has led the 12-month rankings five consecutive times, and is
also the leader for the full 39 months.
   Here's a rundown on what strategists are saying at the 10
brokerage houses. The companies are discussed in order of
their 12-month performance.
                                                                                                       

   PRUDENTIAL-BACHE: Strategist Greg Smith was a raging bull
in 1987 and 1988. Last year he started getting more cautious,
and gradually reduced his recommended stock-market exposure
-- once as high as 100% -- to 35%. Now he's starting to get a
bit more optimistic, recommending a blend of 40% stocks, 40%
bonds and 20% cash. "I still don't think this will be a great
year," he says. But he thinks a lukewarm economy will allow
interest rates to decline, which "will be pretty beneficial
to the stock market." He expects stocks to show a slight loss
in the first half of 1990, but to provide a total return of
5% to 10% for the full year.
                                                                                                       

   SHEARSON: By summer, the inflation numbers that are
currently scaring investors will turn out to have been just
"a flash in the pan," says Michael Sherman, strategist for
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., a unit of American Express Co.
Shearson ranked second for both the 12-month and 39-month
periods. He thinks interest rates on long-term Treasury
bonds, now around 9%, will decline to 8.5% or less within six
months. That would help stocks, because "the current problem
in the stock market is totally related to the bond market."
He predicts the stock market "will hit a new high by the end
of the summer" and recommends a hefty 65% stock position.
                                                                                                       

   SMITH BARNEY: So far this year, Smith Barney, Harris Upham
&amp; Co., a unit of Primerica Corp., has slightly decreased its
recommended stock position to 45% and increased its
allocation for bonds to 35%. In the stock market, "I think at
best we'll see a continuation of the trading range we have
seen," says William Helman, co-chairman of the investment
policy committee. A decline of as much as 15% wouldn't
surprise him, but "I don't think we're looking at a serious,
massive bear market." He doesn't expect big gains from bonds
either, so long as economic strength in Japan, West Germany
and the U.S. keeps "upward pressure" on rates.
                                                                                                       

   GOLDMAN SACHS: We're in for "an uninteresting market" the
next few months, says Steven Einhorn, strategist for Goldman,
Sachs &amp; Co. Stocks won't rise much because of fairly tight
monetary policy world-wide and high interest rates, which he
expects will come down "haltingly" to about 8.5% six months
from now. The rally that began in February in the Dow Jones
Industrial Average hasn't done much for most stocks, Mr.
Einhorn notes. But he says stock prices won't fall very far
because the economy "looks okay," inflation isn't as bad as
people fear, and companies are raising dividends. Prediction:
a range of 2500 to 2800 for the industrial average.
                                                                                                       

   DEAN WITTER: Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., a unit of Sears,
Roebuck &amp; Co., rightly calls itself "the lonely bull."
Strategist John Connolly recommends investors put 85% of
their money in stocks, making him by far the most optimistic
of the 10 strategists. Last quarter, investors who followed
that advice may have regretted it: Dean Witter ranked last
for the quarter with an estimated loss of 2.7%. Longer-term,
it's done better -- third for 39 months and fifth for 12
months. Mr. Connolly says his stance will pay off as
investors realize that the economy is now safely past a
recession but isn't growing fast enough to rekindle
inflation.
                                                                                                       

   MERRILL LYNCH: "The dangers are building up" for the stock
market, says Charles Clough, strategist for Merrill Lynch &amp;
Co. "Interest rates are back up, and earnings are still kind
of weak." For the next few months, he thinks stocks will be
flat to down. But he finds bonds attractive. "Our view is
that a 9% yield is a tremendous amount of value," he says. "A
9% bond doubles in eight years. I think you should lock in
here, or at least begin to." Merrill and A.G. Edwards are the
only two companies that currently suggest investors hold more
bonds than stocks.
                                                                                                       

   KIDDER PEABODY: First in the three-month rankings for the
December quarter, Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co., a subsidiary of
General Electric Co., came in second for the March quarter.
Again, its cautious stance on stocks was vindicated. Dennis
Jarrett, a market analyst, sees "a downward bias" continued,
with the industrial average declining to 2200 or so. "I don't
see any sign that interest rates are going to reverse. I
don't see too many money managers out there ready to be big
bargain hunters," he says. His stock-market prediction:
"General low-volume deterioration." Bonds may get a brief
bounce, he says, but then interest rates are likely to creep
up to 9.25%, as the U.S. Treasury continues to borrow
heavily.
                                                                                                       

   RAYMOND JAMES: Raymond, James &amp; Associates Inc. of St.
Petersburg, Fla., is recommending a "normal" blend containing
60% stocks. J. Davenport Mosby, a managing director, says the
stock market has withstood negative news pretty well, and
that high cash holdings by institutions provide plenty of
fuel for a future rally. Unlike most rivals, Raymond James
sometimes recommends gold and real estate. Currently it urges
a 15% position in real estate, but no gold. It is bearish on
bonds. The spread between short-term and long-term rates is
unusually narrow, and Raymond James thinks it's more likely
that long-term rates will rise than that short-term rates
will fall.
                                                                                                       

   A.G. EDWARDS: Raymond Worseck, strategist at St.
Louis-based A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc., dodged one bullet but
was hit by another. He kept his stock allocation slim, a wise
move in retrospect. But he had a big 45% recommended position
in bonds, which were hurt by rising interest rates. He thinks
both stocks and bonds are due for a rally now, but fears a
new decline later this year. He thinks a reaccelerating
economy, high interest rates abroad and fairly tight monetary
policy by the Federal Reserve will combine to force interest
rates up, hurting both stocks and bonds.
                                                                                                       

   PAINEWEBBER: Customers who followed the PaineWebber Group
Inc. unit's cautious advice largely sidestepped the 7% stock
slide in January, since PaineWebber strategist Edward
Kerschner was recommending only a 25% position in stocks at
the time. As a table that accompanies this story shows, he is
now recommending a 56% allocation to stocks. But that doesn't
mean he is suddenly gotten a whole lot more bullish. Instead,
as explained in the accompanying story, PaineWebber has asked
to be judged on a different set of recommendations (see
related story: "How Quarterly Study Evaluates Brokers'
Allocation of Assets" -- WSJ May 1, 1990).
   For the next few months, stocks are "stuck in a trading
range of 2600 (on the industrial average), plus or minus
10%," Mr. Kerschner says. "Bond yields are nearing their
highs" at around 9%, he says, "but will take some time to
come down." For the moment, he says, the usual state of
affairs is reversed: Skill in picking individual stocks is
more important than asset allocation.
   ---
                 Who Has the Best Blend?
   Performance of Asset-Allocation blends recommended by 10
brokerage houses in periods ended March 31, 1990. Houses are
ranked by 12-month performance. Also shown is the mix each
house now recommends.
                                                                                                       

