<HL>
   Economy:
   Personal Outlays Rose by Modest 0.4%
   In March; New-Home Sales Dipped 5%
   ----
   By Paul Duke Jr.
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
ECONOMIC AND MONETARY INDICATORS (EMI)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Personal spending increased by a moderate
0.4% in March, the Commerce Department reported, as consumers
paid higher prices to keep up with inflation.
   Personal income jumped 0.8%, but much of that stemmed from
a boost in subsidies to farmers; otherwise, the increase was
0.5%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Adjusted for inflation, March personal spending dropped by
0.2% after increasing 0.2% in February and remaining
unchanged in January. However, analysts said the low numbers
don't necessarily mean weakness, as they follow a large 0.8%
increase in December. Several analysts said they expect
inflation-adjusted consumer spending in the second quarter to
show monthly increases of 0.2% or 0.3%.
   "I'm still looking for an upward trend in consumer
spending," said Edward Yardeni, chief economist at
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. "The key to consumer
spending has always been jobs, and they are still expanding."
   In another report, the Commerce Department said sales of
new homes fell 5% in March following a revised 1.5% drop in
February. The March tumble left new-home sales at an annual
rate of 574,000, down from a February rate of 604,000. The
February drop was originally reported as a 3.1% gain. Figures
in both reports are seasonally adjusted.
   "The housing sales numbers look pretty awful," said
Nariman Behravesh, senior vice president at WEFA Group Inc.,
an economic-forecasting company in Bala Cynwyd, Pa. "We're
seeing further bites in the market because of higher interest
rates, especially for longer-term loans."
   With the increase in personal income outstripping personal
spending, the savings rate increased to 5.8% after rising to
5.3% in February and to 5.2% in January. The savings rate is
personal savings divided by disposable personal income.
   On an inflation-adjusted basis, the biggest drop in
personal consumption was a 1.2% decrease in spending on
durable goods -- items intended to last three years or more.
Spending in that category dropped 2.7% in February. The
Commerce Department said lower auto sales caused both
declines. Higher auto sales spurred by discounting fueled a
6.5% increase in durable-goods spending in January.
   Purchases of nondurable goods also dropped, falling 0.9%
after a 0.7% increase in February. Meanwhile, spending on
services increased 0.6% in March after a 0.7% rise the
previous month.
   The 0.4% increase in personal spending before inflation
adjustment followed a revised 0.6% increase in February. The
February increase had originally been reported as 0.4%. The
0.8% personal-income growth in March followed a revised 0.8%
increase in February, originally reported as 0.9%. The
February figure was also affected by farm subsidies; without
them the rise would have been 0.6%.
   "We've seen continued fairly rapid growth in income," said
Jay Woodworth, senior domestic economist at Bankers Trust Co.
"The numbers continue to make a strong case that the Federal
Reserve may need to reconsider interest-rate policy" and
raise rates slightly to head off inflation, he said.
   Mr. Behravesh concurred, saying WEFA Group expects the Fed
to push the federal-funds rate to about 8.5% later in May and
possibly as high as 9% by the end of the summer. This key
interest rate, which is what banks charge one another on
overnight loans, is currently hovering around 8.25%. "There's
a good deal of underlying strength in the economy, and
inflation isn't going away," Mr. Behravesh said.
   ---
   Here is the Commerce Department's latest report on
personal income. The figures are at seasonally adjusted
annual rates in trillions of dollars.
                                                                                                       

                                     March          Feb.
                                     1990           1990
                                                                                                       

   Personal income ................  4.670          4.634
    Wages and salaries ............  2.761          2.747
    Factory payrolls ..............   .565           .561
    Transfer payments .............   .671           .671
                                                                                                       

   Disposable personal income .....  3.993          3.960
                                                                                                       

   Personal outlays ...............  3.762          3.748
    Consumption expenditures ......  3.656          3.642
    Other outlays .................   .107           .107
                                                                                                       

   Personal saving ................   .230           .212
</TEXT>
