<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Why General Mills
   Withdrew New Cereal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A19
</SO>
<CO>
   GIS
</CO>
<LP>
   Your April 3 story on psyllium grain's ability to reduce
cholesterol said:
   "But psyllium isn't without controversy. Last year, the
Food and Drug Administration looked into the safety of its
use in large quantities in cereal. In response, General Mills
Inc. took a psyllium-based cereal off the market."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   General Mills actually removed Benefit from test markets
because of disappointing consumer sales.
   General Mills submitted a 1,313-page petition to the FDA
arguing that psyllium as consumed in Benefit cereal is
completely safe and should be declared "generally recognized
as safe" by the agency.
   R.C. Shulstad
   Director of Public Relations
   General Mills Inc.
   Minneapolis
</TEXT>
