<HL>
   Farm Prices Last Month
   Rose 0.7% From March
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C17
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Farm prices in April rose 0.7% from March,
led by increases in cattle and hog prices, the Agriculture
Department said.
   Average prices received by farmers were 2% higher than in
April 1989, the department said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Beef-cattle prices averaged $75 a hundred pounds, up 80
cents from March, while calf prices averaged $102, up $2.90.
In the hog markets, barrow and gilt prices averaged $53.20 a
hundred pounds in April, up $1.50, while sows averaged
$48.70, up $3.
   Milk prices averaged $13.10 a hundred pounds, down 60
cents from March, the department said. Egg prices averaged
64.2 cents a dozen in April, down 8.9 cents. Broiler prices
fell 3.2 cents to 33.2 cents a pound in April, while turkey
prices slipped 0.2 cents to 37 cents a pound.
   Fruit prices rose 11% in April, led by oranges and
grapefruit, the department said. Vegetable prices fell 13%,
with tomato prices taking a dive.
   Corn prices rose 15 cents to $2.52 a bushel in April,
while sorghum grain rose 22 cents to $3.92 a hundred pounds.
Barley slipped one cent to $2.17 a bushel, while oats fell
two cents to $1.37 a bushel, the department said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900501-0102
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900501-0102.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Mitsubishi to Recall
   Vehicles That Exceed
   Emission Standards
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   J.MOT C
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<GV>
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Mitsubishi Motors of America, the marketing
unit of Mitsubishi Motors Corp., will recall 102,000 of its
1986 passenger cars that exceed the federal emission standard
for carbon monoxide, the Environmental Protection Agency
said.
   The cars, equipped with 1.5-liter engines, are the
Mitsubishi Mirage, the Dodge Colt and Plymouth Colt. All were
built by Mitsubishi, but most were sold by Chrysler Corp.
Chrysler will fix the Dodge and Plymouth cars, the EPA said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The repair, which will be free to car owners, consists of
modifying the carburetor, recalibrating the automatic choke
and, if needed, replacing the secondary air filter.
   Carbon monoxide, which results from incomplete combustion
of fuel, disrupts the delivery of oxygen to the body's organs
and tissues and impairs heart function. It can be especially
harmful to people wih lung disease, anemia and peripheral
vascular disease.
   Car owners will be notified of the recall by mail.
</TEXT>
