<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
05/01/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   MOSLEM MILITANTS FREED an American captive, the second in
eight days.
   Kidnappers in Beirut, putting pressure on Bush to
reciprocate with a goodwill gesture toward Iran, released
Frank Reed, who had been held since September 1986. The
57-year-old educator, who called his captivity "lonely" and
"boring," headed to West Germany after a stop in Syria.
Robert Polhill, freed April 22, delivered a message from his
captors to Bush, who hailed Reed's release and thanked Iran
and Syria. The president also said he'd have "no objection"
if Israel frees a Shiite Moslem cleric, as Tehran has
demanded.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The State Department issued its annual report on
terrorism, which accused Iran of being the "most active state
sponsor" of terrorism last year.
   ---
   A former HUD official told a congressional panel that the
housing agency under Secretary Pierce operated "basically on
political favoritism." DuBois Gilliam, once a deputy
assistant secretary who currently is serving an 18-month
prison term for bribery, said Pierce personally made
decisions on project approvals.
   ---
   NASA engineers untangled a cable on one of the Hubble
Space Telescope's main antennas, a move that could allow at
least limited operation of the orbiting device. Ground
controllers hadn't been able to communicate with the
telescope since its launch Wednesday by the space shuttle
Discovery.
   ---
   A House Democratic task force said El Salvador's inquiry
into last year's killings of six Jesuit priests has come to
"a virtual standstill." The report, which questioned whether
full justice would be done, is expected to influence efforts
to reduce aid to the government of President Cristiani.
   ---
   A citizens' group in Latvia demanded that the Baltic
republic emulate Lithuania and proclaim its independence from
the Soviet Union. The group, claiming to represent hundreds
of thousands of Latvians, termed the republic "an occupied
country." The call came as the legislature prepared to meet
this week to discuss secession.
                                                                                                       

   About 20,000 Lithuanians gathered to mourn a man who
burned himself to death in Moscow last week to protest the
Kremlin's efforts to end the republic's independence bid.
Officials in Vilnius, meanwhile, were quoted as saying the
republic was prepared to suspend its secession drive if
Moscow agrees to open negotiations.
   ---
   West German leaders attempted to overcome Kremlin
opposition to a united Germany's membership in NATO, saying
Bonn wouldn't overlook the Soviet Union's "justified security
interests." The assurances came as the two Germanys and the
four World War II victors prepared to open unification
negotiations Saturday in Bonn.
   ---
   South Korean riot police stormed the headquarters of the
Korean Broadcasting System in Seoul, crushing 19 days of
demonstrations by workers that have disrupted state radio and
television networks. In the southeastern city of Ulsan,
shipyard workers clashed with riot police for a third day,
and labor unrest spread across the nation.
   ---
   Bush conferred in Washington with Panama's President
Endara and announced the nomination of the first-ever
Panamanian to manage the Panama Canal. The president, who
hadn't met with Endara since the U.S. invasion of Panama last
December, also chastised Congress for moving slowly on aid
for the Central American nation.
   ---
   The EPA will issue rules aimed at reducing the amount of
dioxin that gets into water and soil through the making of
bleached paper. The agency said, however, that the risk posed
by dioxin in paper products is "no cause for alarm," and
referred this area to the FDA.
   ---
   The Supreme Court let stand a ruling by a federal appeals
court in New York that abortion-rights groups lack standing
to challenge the tax-exempt status of the Roman Catholic
Church. The justices also let stand a lower-court ruling that
allows random drug testing of Transportation Department
employees who have safety-related jobs.
   ---
   Israel's Herzog called for changes in the nation's
electoral system and criticized politicians for showing a
"total contempt for the principles of democracy." The
president's Independence Day address came amid political
divisions that have blocked formation of a coalition
following the March 15 collapse of Prime Minister Shamir's
government.
   ---
   South Africa's foreign minister said the country's blacks
couldn't push the white minority too far without risking a
backlash that could destroy the nation. His remarks came as
the Pretoria government and the African National Congress
prepared for discussions this week aimed at exploring the
possibility of black-white power-sharing.
   ---
   Authorities in China announced the lifting of martial law
in Tibet's capital. The move came nearly 14 months after the
restrictions were imposed in Lhasa to quell three days of
nationalist rioting that left at least 16 people dead and
more than 100 injured.
   ---
   The U.S. resumed diplomatic relations with the Marxist
government of South Yemen after a break of nearly 21 years.
The country has had close ties with the Soviet Union. In
announcing the move, the State Department said Aden has begun
liberalizing its economy and political system.
</TEXT>
